post_caption: Exploring Tanjong Pagar last weekend. I used to work in this district few years back and i love how it is located in the CBD district yet you can find neighbourhood vibe just along duxton road. More than just cafes and bbq restaurants, you can even find wet market and pasar there. Favourite lunch time meal is roast meat at realty centre.

Did you know that there are a whopping 90 skyscrapers in our little red dot?â €
â €
Interestingly though, in Singapore, it is forbidden to build buildings higher than 280 meters.Â â €
â €
The tallest skyscraper though stands at 290m, like a proud rebel, flouting this rule (ok..ok..they sought a special permission from the Urban Redevelopment Authority)â €
â €
The latest addition to this already-impressive skyline chooses to wow us with itâ€™s shape rather than itâ€™s height. A shiny rounded glass dome that floats on the Singapore river. They say itâ€™s design was inspired by the Pantheon in Rome. A Roman temple inspiring the new-age temple of the Gen Z ,aka, the Apple Showroom. Rather apt.â €
â €
There she stands, sun-bathing, acting as a mirror for the skyline..â €
â €
You wonder, â€œIs this what they mean by reflected glory?â€ :Pâ €
.
.â €
D&I spent an entire morning shooting with this beautiful backdrop! It was our first photoshoot in almost 6 months and we had an absolute ball. Are you guys having fun exploring your home cities as well?

Rediscover Singapore â€˜in Sarisâ€™...

There is an upside to going nowhere during this pandemic.
While borders stay shut and leisure travel remains a forlorn hope, we at DD have decided to explore and checkout our own backyards..
While maintaining social distance in a maximum group of 5, we have set out to enjoy the beauty of our garden city, via all the NParks around the little red dot! 

Follow Rachel as she flags off this journey for the DemureDrapes Singapore! 
Here she travels to 
Sunplaza park in Tampines, 
Bedok Reservoir park in Bedok, 
the Tampines eco green Diversity and Forest trails, 
Pasir Ris mangroves,
Changi Board Walk,
East Coast Park,
Henderson Waves, 
Telok Blangah park,
Mount Faber..

To start the walk tours for  rediscovering Singapore, as team DD explores different parks, we will share details.

Letâ€™s together rediscover the Jewel we live in..

A simple step out of your comfort zone can make you realise that nothing is impossible, as long as you allow your heart to embrace whatever comes.

Being someone with height phobia and having occasions of rolling out of my own bed, sleeping on the upper bunk of a double decker bed is considered as a simple step out of comfort zone.

|
How long will our appreciation for essential workers last? Will we continue thanking the aunties and uncles who work hard behind the scenes so that we can pose infront of picturesque backgrounds for our instagram feed? Our gratitute towards essential workers should not be momentary. Instead the habit of saying "Thank you for your hardwork today" - should be a habit cultivated and ingrained in us. 
|
I am grateful to have captured one of the most meaningful and significant moment during my trip to Gardens by the Bay.

Pasir Ris mangroves is small, but has a lovely boardwalk running through it. It allows a close up look at the fascinating mangroves! Such as the mud lobster mounds which are rarely seen nowadays. The boardwalk meanders among tall mangrove trees. Allowing us a closer look at the plants as well as the animals living in the mud and pools and streams. The boardwalk leads to a lovely little shelter on Sungei Tampines. It's a great spot to look at birds and fishes and snakes! Pasir Ris is the only place on the mainland where we can easily view rare mangrove trees.

The word Bharata is a mnemonic, consisting of "bha"â€“"ra"â€“"ta". According to a belief, bha stands for bhava (feelings, emotions), ra stands for raga (melody, framework for musical notes), and ta stands for tala (rhythm). The term Natya is a Sanskrit word for "dance".

It was 1930 when the worldâ€™s first tropical dairy farm was established at the base of Bukit Timah Hill. Originally, the area was earmarked for pig farming but after an outbreak of swine fever, Fred Heron, Managing Director of Cold Storage, decided that there was a need for high quality, fresh milk in Singapore and converted the area to a milk farm instead.

He brought in 24 Friesian cows to Singapore from Holland and Australia and started a dairy farm in the area. Hence, setting down the basis for Dairy Farm Nature Parkâ€™s name.

Friesian cattle are a breed known for their dairy production. They are completely alien to the tropics and the Singapore dairy farm was an oddity that attracted a fair amount of worldwide attention.

Today, the cows are gone. Nonetheless, they still resound with the name Dairy Farm Nature Park.

The #Best #calamari in #singapore , and a really nice #club with #great #service . We were here just before #cb #circuitbreaker in April, and 5.5mths later, we are back. I had many calamari before, but this is the only one I couldn't forget and I just want more of it. My friend and I are such fans we decided to get our own plate each next time. Not only was the batter really crispy and #delicious , but the spicy #mayo too. 

Plus,  the club has its own pool for that #instagram moment,  not so much for swim as now, it's limited to 20mins only. A bird drank my coconut whilst we were in the pool, and an attentive staff told us on our return that he had cleared the coconut and offered me a new one. Super great and responsible service eh? 

We were here 2x and we still love the food and #vibe here.  Hope to be back again, and with no crowds (surprisingly being a weekday, it was rather full!).

Weather was perfect,  wasn't hot, wasn't rainy. I was really happy, thanks to my friend's indulgence to also have a dip in the pool with me (she wasn't quite feeling the mood for the pool).

Archaeological excavations of artefacts such as Chinese coins or ceramics in Singapore, which dated back to the period of the reign of Emperor Zhenzong of Song (998â€“1022) and Emperor Renzong of Song (1023â€“1063), indicated that Chinese merchants or traders had already visited Singapore since Song dynasty. But when Singapore became a Straits Settlement, there were very few Chinese. After Singapore became a British trading post as part of the Straits Settlement, the first batch of Chinese came from Malaysia, predominantly from Malacca and Penan. The Chinese quickly formed the majority of the population in Singapore. After interacting with diverse influences over many years, Chinese culture in Singapore has evolved in a way quite unlike other communities around the world. No matter who you are, there is always room to discover (rediscover ) what it means to be a Chinese Singapoäºº

post_caption:
Being stuck in a little island ainâ€™t so bad. Letâ€™s  make the best of it to rediscover Singapore ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬ !
*****
My friends and I took a short 10
mins bum boat ride to Pulau Ubin. We hired a premium mountain bike ($15) and cycled from east to west of the little island. We hiked the tallest hill Bukit Pakau which is only 74m in height but the views were rewarding! The most challenging cycling trail was on our way to Chek Jawa wetlands. You need strong thighs and a good momentum cycling uphill on rocky trails. Otherwise you get off the bike and just walk. We saw hornbills, monkeys, wild boar of all ages and other friendly fellow cyclists. We end our day with a late seafood lunch and a well deserving cold coconut!
*****
Bum boat rides available at Changi Point Ferry Terminal for $4 per pax, one way.
*****

63km lsd done yesterday covering west to east to northeastern Singapore.. Selfie at the Sunset strip along Punggol Reservoir with the dome-shaped trellis (Jewel Bridge) as a background! ğŸ˜Š

Last month, I went out of Singapore's mainland. But no, I didn't travel out of Singapore. Some of my friends and family thought that I can now travel overseas; but sadly, that's not the case. I'm still confined in this tiny red dot.

I miss the feeling of traveling, of leaving my comfort zone and explore new places. For now, the Southern Islands are the farthest places I can travel to, and that's okay. 

Kusu island is one of the many Southern Islands located off the southern coast of Singapore. It is home to a beautiful Chinese temple, a sacred Malay shrine, a cute tortoise shelter and 2 beaches.

I have visited this island twice and it's still one of my favorite islands in Singapore. It is just so beautiful and it doesn't feel like Singapore at all. 

If you are planning to visit Kusu island, please bring your own food and drink because you won't be able to buy any on the island. Before you go, do read my detailed guide for visiting Kusu Island. Link in bio!

During the Second World War, a hill in the park was the site of one of the last and fiercest battles fought by the Malay Regiment against the invading Japanese army, the Battle of Bukit Chandu. 
Kent Ridge Park is part of the Pasir Panjang Historic District, which focuses on World War II battlefield events in western Singapore. 
Near to the top of the ridge, there is a commemorative heritage site marker which shows the area where the Battle of Pasir Panjang of 1942 was fought.

And I love it! â¤ï¸ Behind this facade there are layers and layers of memories, each telling a different aspect of the areas history. But the constant remodelling of Singapore has had one positive impact: Contemporary Singapore architecture has a strong focus on sustainability! The history of Sri Srinivasa Perumal temple dates back to the late 1800s when influential community leaders like Mr Arunachala Pillay, Mr Cootaperumal Pillay, Mr Ramasamy Pillay, Mr Appasamy Pillay, Mr Chockalingam Pillay and Mr Ramasamy Jamidar, all of whom had close working links with the East Indian Company, wanted to build a Hindu temple for Vaishnavite worship.

These men got together and purchased a piece of land measuring 2 acres 2 woods and 24 poles from the East India Company in 1851 for 26 rupees and 8 annas (at that period of time Indian currency was still used in the Settlement of Singapore). The temple they built in 1885 was referred to as the Narasinga Perumal Kovil.

This grew as more devotees donated land to the temple.

The 20-metres-tall impressive Gopuram is a relatively recent addition, built in 1966.
.
.
.
.
.

Spent a lovely morning catching up with the ex schoolmate at this quaint bakery cafe and didn't realise how much the shops have changed since a long time ago when I used to hang out along the stretch during my schooling years.ğŸ˜‘

If the bakery selection reminds you of a certain more renowned oneğŸ˜œ, I have to say the food is slightly less expensive here but waaaayyy better in quality and taste! I really love the 3 items we selected: ğŸ¥“ğŸ¥§ Bacon Quiche, Chicken and Cheese Bun and Mini Pain au Chocolat. The quiche was super yummy, the bacon and cheese filling went really well with the buttery pie crust. The Chicken and Cheese Bun was also very good, I like how the milk bread was slightly crispy and the filling was the right hint of savoury chicken-pieness though I wish there was a bit more of it. 

The ğŸ¥ğŸ«Pain au Chocolat was light and shatteringly delicious! You know how some chocolate croissants tend to leave a heavy taste on the palate...for me this was almost perfect and the chocolate was not too sweet. It has just the right hints of cocoa and ğŸ§ˆ butter. I would exercise an entire week just to eat this again soon! ğŸ˜… 

Post-note: I found out some interesting facts about the ingredients used in their breads from their website and the head chef is a very prolific baker from Japan. I would definitely need to come back soon! ğŸ˜

post_caption: Singapore ğŸ¥°fascinates me (and I am sure a lot of other people) by how the change in human and heritage landscape has been very significant. Behind this modern facade today there are layers and layers of memories, each telling a different aspect of the areas history. Many beautifully preserved examples of shophouses on hand today (constructed between the 1840s and the 1960s) across the island remain a visible canvas that portrays Singaporeâ€™s intriguing multicultural and architectural influences throughout the years. In 1970s and 1980s Singapore, pre-war shophouses were demolished to make way for urban development. Unfortunately, many of the tiles found in these buildings were sadly thrown out, but thanks to some passionate individuals, a number of them were saved, restored and preserved. With its intricacy and artistic detail, it is not hard to see why these tiles became a requisite of the Peranakan decorative repertoire (check out the storiesğŸ™ƒğŸ‘†ğŸ»if you want to know more about it) #singaporeğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬ #architecture #rediscoversingapore #painting #workshop @capellasingapore #ÑĞ¸Ğ½Ğ³Ğ°Ğ¿ÑƒÑ€  #art  #coffee #interiordesign #Ñ‚ĞµĞ»Ğ¾Ğ²Ğ´ĞµĞ»Ğ¾  @sassymamasg #sassymamasg #longboard #expatlivingsg @expatlivingsg #tattoo #graffiti #timeoutsg #meditation  #hipster @channelnewsasia #visitsingapore @visit_singapore #singaporeinsiders  #photography #jewelrydesigner  @chanelofficial  #chanel  @instagram #travelphotography  #kidsactivities

Magazine Road connects Havelock Road and Merchant Road. The road probably got its name due to its association with the old ammunition storage ground at Havelock Road. The road used to run along the Singapore River before reclamation and road works took place sometime in the 1980s. 

I cycled here one morning to check out the Tan Si Chong Su, the ancestral hall of the Tan Clan dating back to 1876. I was also surprised to find this brick structure that reminded me of Ximending's Red House in Taipei. 

From here one could also see the the Chin Swee flats constructed in the 1970s. In the background are also several mdoern architectural landmarks such as the 1974 Manhattan House by S.E.K Architects and most notably, the Landmark Tower, completed in 1985, designed by the late Timothy Seow, the architect behind the NTU School of  Arts, Design at Nanyang Technological University.

Also located in the vicinity is the famous Red Star Restaurant, founded in 1974 and known for their old school dim sum with trolley service. Further down from Magazine Road, and turning into Keng Cheow Street, you will find Masjid Omar Kampong Melaka, Singapore's oldest mosque dating back to 1820.

Fort Canning Hill area was once the centre of ancient Singapura that thrived in the 14th century, and was occupied by a palace with various buildings of political, religious and commercial significance.

 A spring used to exist on the west side of the hill, called pancur larangan or "forbidden spring", where the women of the ruler's household were said to bathe in ancient times. Many locals still call it the â€˜Forbidden Hill and believe it is haunted as many have reported loud noises and thumps in park at night, as well as sightings of white hooded figures.

The hill, however, continued to be used by Imperial British forces and a massive underground bunker was built to serve as headquarters of the local military district.

Although the area is not very large, about 18 acres, there is so much to see. Unfortunately, there are no remains of the medieval palace that once dominated the hill. #fortcanning #fortcanningpark #singapore #sgig #iluvsg #rediscoversingapore #sosingaporelah #spiralstaircase

#3 of #11 lessons: 
Some of us has the perspective that cooking takes a huge amount of effort, when meals an be prepared simply.

On my very first night, a German couple was preparing their dinner and I was surprised that they managed to prepare a bowl of vermicelli with vegetables and topped with sauce. 
Though I found out there's a mini rice cooker and an induction cooker with the pantry cupboards towards the end of my stay, they managed to use the electric water kettle to prepare their dinner. 
Isn't that inspiring for us create simple meals?

Today there are five different lines in the â€œsubwayâ€/â€œtubeâ€ system. The first line was the red line (north south) and it was launched in 1987. Following that was the green line from east to west in 1990. I remember taking it often when I was a kid when we visited my grandparents.
.
Part of the lines are built overground (swipe left) while the stations located in the central are mostly located underground.
.
The newest is the blue line (Down town line) that was built in 2013.

post_caption:
Fukushima Junmai Ginjo - un soire au chez @toku_izakaya_bar
.
Fukushima has a long history as a reputable sake region, with many of the prefectureâ€™s 60 breweries dating back over 300 years. But it was the aftermath of the Tohoku Earthquake of 2011 that really propelled local brewers to strive for sake excellence; they united together to not only rebuild the local sake industry after the disaster, but to improve it. Uniquely, the producers share their knowledge on brewing methods, which are usually heavily guarded trade secrets. The variety of climates in Fukushima result in quite different brews: the mountainous inland area of Aizu-Wakamatsu is known for a richer, sweeter, more umami-laden type of sake to match the more hearty cuisine, while the coastal region of Hamadori brews light and refreshing varieties to match the local seafood.
. 
Ginjo (åŸé†¸) is premium sake that uses rice that has been polished to at least 60 percent. It is brewed using special yeast and fermentation techniques. The result is often a light, fruity, and complex flavor that is usually quite fragrant.
.
The pairing between Junmai Ginjo and  a bitter Japanese Ginko with bonito flake create a sensational sweet flavour in the mouth. Unexpected recommendation from chef Masamitsu Kodamatsu. ğŸ‘ğŸ½
.

Tug in a quite residential neighbourhood in Hougang holds an important legacy of the Japanese in Singapore.
The sprawling 30,000-square-metre Japanese Cemetery Park contains nearly 1,000 graves of Japanese civilians in Singapore and soldiers mostly from the early 20thÂ century. This is the largest Japanese cemetery in Southeast Asia.
Founded by three Japanese brothel-keepers, the cemetery was built in 1891 as a burial ground for karayuki-san, or Japanese women brought here for prostitution, many of whom died poor and destitute.
Over the years, other Japanese civilians were buried here, mostly during the pre-war years. The cemetery was a burial ground until 1947, and became a memorial park in 1987. The Japanese Association of Singapore oversees its upkeep.
The well-kept park also holds the ashes of Japanese soldiers, marines and airmen killed during World War II, as well as the remains of Japanese war criminals who were executed at Changi Prison.

Among them are Tanah Merah I and Tanah Merah II, bungalowsÂ built in the 1880s to accommodate the British Officers of the Royal Artillery, Coastal Defence Command based on Sentosa Island.Â Known as the Officers'Â Mess, it was where the officers and their families ate and relaxed by dancing and playing tennis.Â â£
They were given conservation status on Aug 7, 2000.â£

Fort Canning Park, an iconic hilltop landmark has witnessed many of Singaporeâ€™s historical milestones. The hill once sited the palaces of 14th century Kings and served as the Headquarters of the Far East Command Centre and British Army Barracks. The decision to surrender Singapore to the Japanese on 15 February 1942 was also made on the hill, in the Underground Far East Command Centre, commonly known as Battle Box.

Today, Fort Canning Park features nine historical gardens - the Pancur Larangan, Artisanâ€™s Garden, Sang Nila Utama Garden, Jubilee Park, Raffles Garden, First Botanic Garden, Farquhar Garden, Spice Garden and Armenian Street Park.
The total length of the trail is about 2.5km. 
The park was originally known as Bukit Larangan, or 'Forbidden Hill' in Malay. 
Fort Canning â€”a verdant space surrounded by 18th century gateways and gazebos, was our first stop in our journey to

#beautiful #temple of the #earth #god sitting with a moat. It was raining heavily, but it is a picture of #tranquility in the raging rain. It feels like overseas, and I wish I have more time to walk about and explore rather than the 15 mins or so I visit the island every 10 years or so. 

The middle aged couple living there tending to the temple must be feeling quite isolated from life on the mainland. The uncle I spoke to says it needs getting used to. But then I was also thinking, you get a peaceful life and an island to yourselves, isnt that great? Maybe in freedom, there is also a responsibility (manning the temple), and maybe isolation and peaceful life isn't such a great thing?

ğŸ“Chijmesâ£â£
CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and â€˜MESâ€™ was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.â£
â£â£
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840â€“1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. (Source: Wikipedia)â£â£

The history of bubble tea in Singapore began when the drink was first introduced to the country in 1992. It has undergone a few waves of popularity here.Â In the old days, bubble tea was served in a cocktail glass in â€œbubble tea hutsâ€. But long queues at bubble tea shops, now serving only takeaway bubble tea, is a common sight today. How has this craze managed to sustain itself for this long and continue to find favour among Singaporeans? So long story short, while many regard it as a fad, others deem it to be a classic example of how a simple drink can continue to appeal to different taste preferences and be enjoyed by people across generations... in 5 years I decided to try it ğŸ˜‚finally! Telok Kurau Road
connects Changi Road to Marine Parade Road and was named after a fishing village named Telok Kurau on East Coast Road. According to Infopedia, the name, Telok Kurau, means "mango fish bay" in Malay. Mango Fish (Polynemus risua) is in the threadfin family. More commonly however, Ikan Kurau is also used to refer to "threadfin", also known as "ngoh her" in Hokkien.

I cycled here recently after reading up on Siglap. The site in this illustration is the junction of Joo Chiat Place and Telok Kurau Road. The unit where Fu Fa Coffeeshop is right now was previously occupied by Long Fu Coffeeshop (éš†ç¦). One of its stalls was Nam Huat Chicken Rice (å—ç™¼é›é£¯) which started business in the 1970s and closed in 2014.

Next to the coffeeshop was Chang Cheow Ser, a 24-year old provision shop which started in the former Siglap Market. The provision shop was named after it's founder and it had a distinct iron grill facade. The unit has been taken over by Sunric Stores (a convenience store).

The row of single-storey structures here are located opposite the former Telok Kurau West Primary School which first opened in 1962. It joined two other schools, the Telok Kurau Malay Girls' School and Telok Kurau East School to form Telok Kurau Primary School in 1985. The current school's earliest history goes back to 1926 as the Telok Kurau English School. The late Mr Lee Kuan Yew studied there in 1931.

Each Supertree is made up of four major components: the reinforcement concrete core, the trunk, planting panels, and a canopy. Designed to resemble trees, theyâ€™re meant to function like them as well. 
Some are equipped with solar panels to store energy for the nightly light show, while others are used as air exhaust receptacles to help cool the Flower Dome and Cloud Forest conservatories. On top of that, they all collect rainwater for use in irrigation and fountain displays. Photosynthesis, cooling the air, and storing rainwater, like actual trees indeed!

This temple building was constructed in 1930 with a donation from Aw Boon Haw and Aw Boon Par, brothers best known for developing the Tiger Balm ointment. They are, of course, the brothers who also built Haw Par Villa. 

ğŸª”The temple is 15 metres tall and houses a 300-ton statue of Buddha. 

ğŸª”The statue is surrounded by a seemingly endless chain of lights, leading to the templeâ€™s popular name, â€œTemple of a Thousand Lightsâ€. 

ğŸª” it houses an ebony and mother-of-pearl replica of Buddhaâ€™s footprint and a piece of bark from the original Bodhi tree under which Buddha sat. This replica of the footprint was found on top of Adamâ€™s Peak in Sri Lanka, a mountain named after the belief that its summit housed the first man Adamâ€™s crypt. 

ğŸª”The templeâ€™s architecture reflects an eclectic mix of Chinese, Thai and Indian cultural influences.

It has no lights or pavements. the wildlife at Tampines Eco Green is still quite rich. opened in 2011, the Tampines Eco Green Park is a nature-loverâ€™s delight. In the middle of high-density HDB flats, this 36.5 hectare park, situated in the east of our island nation, is home to a wealth of biodiversity.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

The saddest thing about the day trip was: I wanted to see Lazarus the most, but we just ended up walking in heavy thunderstorm,  never made it to the beach, and all we did was spent time under a shelter to wait out the heavy rain with a sad kitty hiding from the cold in the grass patch,  and a earthworm (I think) for company.  I left our lunch bag somewhere, dont know where, and we didn't have lunch. Lols. Makes the trip all that more memorable, isnt it? We had to make our way back to St John for the boat, and we managed to find our lunch bag sitting in the rain. Lols. I left it on the floor when taking a picture, and  ran off without it and it sat in the thunderstorm for over an hour. Nice. Monkeys were climbing over the roofs of the gazebos, and we had to head for the pier to have our  lunch and some shelter. What a day!

The majestic and imposing City Hall has been the focal point of many of the most important events in the history of Singapore.
-	Admiral Lord Louis Mountbatten, on behalf of the Allied forces, accepted the surrender of the Japanese forces on 12 September 1945 in City Hall to end World War II in Singapore
.
-	On 5 June 1959, Mr Lee Kuan Yew declared self-governance and together with his eight cabinet ministers took their Oaths of Allegiance and Oaths of Office in the City Hall Chamber
.
-	The Malaysia Proclamation was read out here in 1963 when Singapore was no longer under British rule. The first Malaysia Day was also held at the Padang which was outside the City Hall
.
-	When Singapore was no longer part of Malaysia, the first National Day Parade was also held at the Padang in 1966. The steps of the City Hall have since been used as a VIP seating area when National Day Parades were held there, the latest being the 2020 NDP held recently
.
-	The City Hall was also the place where Singaporeâ€™s second Prime Minister, Mr Goh Chok Tong had his inauguration ceremony and the swearing-in of his cabinet in 1990
.
-	In 2015, The City Hall, together with the adjacent Old Supreme Court Building, has been converted into the National Gallery Singapore
.
As an officially gazetted National Monument of Singapore since 14 February 1992, do take some time to visit this historic building together with the Old Supreme Court Building (which was also gazetted as a National Monument)
.
.

I have seen so many photos of everyone coming here to catch a glimpse of the first Apple floating Store, guess I am one of the last few people who comes here after all the hype is over. This place used to be bustling with evening joggers and visitors from both local and abroad. Nowadays its just peaceful and calm. Even the water taxis are no longer in operation. I believe that most places would be the same but its somehow another unique experience. It feels great to be out again!
.
Photo taken with Kase plug in filter in the Nikon Z 7. I rate this filter 7/10 for quality, no color cast, affordable and highly versatile. The 3 points deducted were for the scary experience mounting it on and off and cannot be easily changed on the go.

The three of us have decided that when we meet, we do something thatâ€™s out of our comfort zone. We chose to go on a walk this time and someoneâ€™s prawn mee craving sealed our route/end point. We flagged off @gardensbythebay, walked high and low round the bay, through the Sports Hub, Tanjung Rhu, Kampong Arang, down Katong where we made a pit stop @bopgelato, and finally crossed the checkered flag at Beach Road Prawn Mee. 
During our 11+ km walk, we spoke about anything and everything - where we would go if we could travel (have you had difficult travelling companions and how did you cope?); Covid conspiracy theories; NS memories (not mine); Emily in Paris (so bad yet addictive); Birkin bags; and what our next â€˜adventureâ€™ should be. I think the conversations kept our feet moving.
.

Kampong â€“ a term to describe traditional villages or urban slum areas in towns and cities. 

In the early days, there used to be many kampongs scattered all over Singapore. However, with development and urbanization, these kampongs have been replaced with modern skyscrapers.

As an urban kid, kampong lifestyle is something that I find it hard to visualize and the only references I have of it are from my grandparentsâ€™ narration of their happy childhood days back in the kampong era.

Upon knowing that there is still the last kampong in Singapore (Kampong Lorong Buangkok), I jumped at the chance to explore it. It was a strange feeling walking through the kampong. Despite being surrounded by the all-so-familiar modern architectures and bustling roads, time seemed to come to a standstill here. Low-rise single-storey houses made of wood with zinc roofs instead of high-rise apartments; lush greeneries instead of dense man-made structures; a peaceful and quiet surrounding instead of the hustle and bustle of the city, this is indeed a whole new world to me!

I took my time to explore and admire the place, soaking up the atmosphere of this lovely location (and at the same time trying very hard to ignore the constant attacks from the bloodsucking mosquito..). This visit has definitely changed my impression of Singapore â€“ there is more to Singapore than meets the eye!!

A very impromptu decision to visit The S.E.A Aquarium this morning and a decision which paid off!
Both boys were excited from the moment they reached the entrance and ran amok inside! It was surprising there was a fair amount of visitiors even at 10am in the morning and the Safety Distance Ambassadors had their hands full coordinating the crowd! Aldon was so excitied throughout the day after visiting that he drew his impression of a ship wreck in the blue ocean and various sea animals during his arts class in the late evening! All in all, a great Sunday bonding with the boys!
Fyi - They are running a special promotion for Singaporeans and PRs at the SEA Aquarium til 31st August! Discounted ticket prices + Free Liho bubble tea per ticket purchased!

#familytime #ilovemytwoboys #sentosa #seaaquarium #RediscoverSingapore

Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on.

Please don't feed the monkeys ğŸµ 
You will do them more harm than good ! With  human development encroaching further and further into their habitat, we have become close neighbours ... Macaques have come to learn that humans provide easy access to food and continue to rely on them. Sadly, a lack of education on appropriate human behaviours around wildlife has led to a rise in human-macaque interaction and conflict. For example, people feed monkeys to have a closer look at these fascinating creatures. Some people even think the monkeys are starving. 
In 2019 the Jane Goodall Institute Singapore (JGIS) in partnership with the Longtailed Macaque Working Group launched the campaign to solve this problem: a three-year "No Feeding" campaign aims to teach park-goers and residents near macaque hotspots not to feed the monkeys. Did you hear anything about â€œMonkey Guardsâ€? A team of residents in hotspots who have been trained in macaque behaviour and appropriate ways of dealing with them. The aim isnâ€™t to eliminate the sightings of macaques, but to create a safe and respectful barrier between people and macaques. I went to this rustic island off the north eastern part of Singapore, knowing that the weather wasnâ€™t too favourable.

Thankfully it was bright and sunny for at least the first half of the day and it only rained extremely heavily for about 45 minutes, in which I thankfully managed to seek refuge at Ah Maâ€™s Drink Stall.

From climbing up to see beautiful quarries, to seeing random shrines and temples. From wild boar and big lizard scares to feeding thirsty dogs with half of my water. From beautiful butterflies to nasty spiders. My adventure to this tranquil island is made more tranquil with much lesser crowds and social distancing.

Yet, I feel full and energised. I feel rejuvenated and refreshed. And I feel glad to have learnt so much on this trip and to have feel so much in touch with the finer things in life.

Dear Pulau Ubin, or rather, Pulau Batu Jubin, thank you so much for the fun! So great to see you after 5 over years! My stamina may not be there, but my spirit is still going strong! Take care and till next time!

After the walk is feasting time. @littleislandbrew has a good range of craft beer and the food is fantastic. We love the freshly made pizza ğŸ•, soft and tender beef brisket. The beauty of cities is that they offer us unexpected moments, serendipitous encounters. Today, that came in the form of running into @yipyewchong who is the artist of many of the street art of Chinatown. Using these murals as our laboratory, the life of the early Chinese immigrants comes alive with his artwork. In this case, the dazzling costumes, realistic backdrops, props and acrobatic fighting of Cantonese Opera which was all around early Chinatown.

Psst : the full length of this colourful mural will be posted on IG stories tomorrow (friyay!)

Lastly, big thanks YC for taking time to chat with our friends this morning!

During the Second World War, a hill in the park was the site of one of the last and fiercest battles fought by the Malay Regiment against the invading Japanese army, the Battle of Bukit Chandu. 
Kent Ridge Park is part of the Pasir Panjang Historic District, which focuses on World War II battlefield events in western Singapore. 
Near to the top of the ridge, there is a commemorative heritage site marker which shows the area where the Battle of Pasir Panjang of 1942 was fought.

You can find us at:

30 Tai Seng Street, #02-14
BreadTalk IHQ
Singapore 534013
Mon to Sat: 10 am to 7 pm
Email: hello@mightyvelo.com

We donâ€™t have a phone line nor Wifi yet so you can email us at hello message us for any bike enquiries.

You can book a test ride with us via hello message us at Mighty Velo - the Folding Bike Specialist. 

We are now accepting pre orders for all Birdy models.

If you want to get the 5% discount that will end on 31 August, you will need to pre order at our store or via email and pay by Paynow to us before 31 Aug.

We will need to observe safe distancing measures at the new store and will onlu be able to allow a certain number of customers into our store at any one time.

We will not be accepting Brompton biek servicing and repairs until further notice next week.

There will also be no instant bike repairs and servicing at our store and customers will need to leave the bikes behind.

We will not be encouraging customers to linger at the store for more than 30 minutes.

Each test ride (includes asking questions) will be 30 minutes long and each test ride can only have a max of 3 in the group.
